subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis.
Recognized by the following combination of characters: female clypeus with narrow apical emargination (
Fig. 2
), cephalic foveae placed in a subtriangular shallow depression (
Fig. 3
), male clypeus broader than long and semicircularly emarginate (
Fig. 4
), F11 digitiform and evenly curved (
Fig. 5
), pronotal carina complete and rounded on humeri, transverse carina of metanotum arcuate and dull, posterior lobe of tegula long and narrow (
Fig. 6
), posterolateral corners of propodeum with short tubercles, apical margin of T1 translucent, T2 with apical reflexed lamella, T3 of male with short translucent lamella (
Fig. 7
), coloration black and orange, with apical band on T2 narrow medially and abruptly expanded on sides.

Like female, differing as follows: head in frontal view 1.2 × as wide as long, clypeus in frontal view 1.1 × as wide as long, free apical part much shorter than basal interocular part, apical margin semicircularly emarginate and 0.3 × as wide as clypeal width (
Fig. 4
), clypeus in lateral view more convex in basal two thirds, mandible 3-toothed with apical tooth straight and longer than wide, second tooth prolonged in a long cutting margin that occupies about half of inner margin, third tooth subtriangular, short with a very broad base, upper margin adhering to lateral margin of clypeus, F11 digitiform and evenly curved in lateral view, reaching apical third of F8 (
Fig. 5
), gena in lateral view 1.4 × as broad as eye at bottom of ocular sinus, T3 with short apical translucent lamella (
Fig. 7
); clypeus, ventral side of scape and broad marking above interantennal space bright yellow, transverse band on metanotum and longitudinal line on posterolateral corners of propodeum orange.
